Plot Genes

Plot Genes

This example shows how to determine the position of some genes in the genome and create a plot showing them. We’ll use TxDb.Hsapiens.UCSC.hg19.knownGene and org.Hs.eg.db Bioconductor packages to map the gene symbols into Entrez Gene Ids and we’ll use those to get the gene positions from the TxDb object.

library("org.Hs.eg.db")
library("TxDb.Hsapiens.UCSC.hg19.knownGene")

symbols <- c("BRCA1", "BRCA2", "PALB2", "NF1", "ERBB3", "PTEN",
             "TP53", "RB1", "EED", "EZH2")

geneids <- select(org.Hs.eg.db, keys=symbols, columns=c("ENTREZID"), keytype="ALIAS")
rownames(geneids) <- geneids$ENTREZID

txdb <- TxDb.Hsapiens.UCSC.hg19.knownGene
all.genes <- genes(txdb)
sel.genes <- all.genes[all.genes$gene_id %in% geneids$ENTREZID]

gene.labels <- geneids[sel.genes$gene_id, "ALIAS"]

sel.genes
## GRanges object with 11 ranges and 1 metadata column:

Once we have the data prepared we can use kpPlotMarkers to plot them on the genome.

library(karyoploteR)
kp <- plotKaryotype(genome="hg19")
kpPlotMarkers(kp, data=sel.genes, labels=gene.labels)

The gene labels are not readable since they overlap the ideograms. To solve this we will tweak the plot a bit: make the labels horizontal, reduce them and move them closer to their ideograms specifying lower r1 and adjusting the label.margin.

kp <- plotKaryotype(genome="hg19")
kpPlotMarkers(kp, data=sel.genes, labels=gene.labels, text.orientation = "horizontal",
              r1=0.4, cex=0.5, label.margin = -60, adjust.label.position = FALSE)
